 Namibia on Wednesday said it recorded 45 COVID-19 deaths, the highest daily increase since the virus was reported in the country in March, 2020.  Kalumbi Shangula, the Health Minister said in a statement that 45 cases were recorded from 10 districts in the country. “With concern, we continue to record a high number of deaths due to COVID-19. “ Patients are urged to visit health facilities as early as possible for medical assistance, late health seeking behavior leads to high mortality,’’ he said. Namibia has so far recorded 77, 333 COVID-19 positive cases with a cumulative number of 1,224 deaths. (Xinhua/NAN) By Cecilia Ologunagba Abuja - World Health Organisation (WHO) says there is a 23 per cent increase in the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Africa in the past week. WHO disclosed this in a weekly COVID-19 Situation update for WHO Africa Region, External Situation Report 21, posted on… In "Health" File photo By Cecilia Ologunagba ABUJA - The World Health Organisation (WHO) says 10 countries account for 88 per cent  (440,672) of all reported Coronavirus (COVID19) cases in the African Region. WHO Regional Office for Africa in Brazzaville, Congo, disclosed this in a report posted on its official Twitter account… In "News" ABUJA - The World Health Organisation (WHO) says the number of  confirmed Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases in Africa  has risen to over 175, 000. The WHO Regional Office for Africa in Brazzaville, Congo, gave the update on Saturday on its official twitter handle @WHOAFRO. “There are over 175,000 confirmed COVID-19… In "News"